    "legal_usage": "The defendant in a criminal trial has constitutional rights, including the right to counsel, to confront witnesses, and to remain silent. They are presumed innocent until proven guilty. In civil cases, the defendant responds to the plaintiff's complaint and can be held liable if the plaintiff meets the burden of proof. In courtroom address, criminal defendants are often referred to by name or as \"the defendant,\" while civil defendants can be individuals or organizations (e.g., \"Defendant Corporation\").",
