    "simplified": "欺诈",
    "traditional": "欺詐",
    "definition": "Wrongful or criminal deception intended to result in financial or personal gain. It involves deliberate misrepresentation or concealment of important facts.",
    "legal_usage": "Fraud can be a crime (e.g., insurance fraud, credit card fraud) or a civil tort. To prove fraud in court, one generally must show a false statement or deceit, knowledge of its falsity, intent to induce reliance, actual reliance by the victim, and resulting harm. California law recognizes various fraud offenses: grand theft by false pretenses, securities fraud, etc. In civil cases, fraud can lead to compensatory and sometimes punitive damages due to the malicious intent. A person defrauded can also seek to rescind contracts induced by fraud.",
