    "mk": 9,
    "idi": 6,
    "simplified": "大陪审团",
    "traditional": "大陪審團",
    "definition": "A panel of citizens convened to investigate potential criminal conduct and determine whether criminal charges should be brought (by issuing indictments). Unlike a trial (petit) jury, a grand jury does not decide guilt or innocence.",
    "legal_usage": "Grand juries operate in secret. In federal court and many states, they are used to review evidence presented by prosecutors in serious cases. California uses grand juries for certain indictments and also has civil grand juries to investigate local government. Grand jurors hear evidence and witness testimony (often with only the prosecutor present, no judge or defense counsel) and then vote on whether there is probable cause to indict (issue a true bill). At least 12 grand jurors (out of typically 19) in California must concur to indict. Proceedings are one-sided and defendants usually don't testify. This process can lead to an indictment, which is then prosecuted in court.",
