    "traditional": "法定監 護人",
    "definition": "A guardian appointed by the court to represent the interests of a minor child or an incapacitated person during legal proceedings. The term is Latin for \"guardian for the lawsuit.\"",
    "legal_usage": "A guardian ad litem (GAL) acts as the voice of a child or incompetent person in court cases such as custody disputes, child abuse cases, or probate matters involving someone who cannot advocate for themselves. In California juvenile dependency cases, for instance, minors automatically get a GAL (often their attorney acts in that capacity). In civil lawsuits, a minor must have a GAL to sue or defend. The GAL's duty is to make decisions in the best interest of the person they represent and to inform the court of that person's welfare or wishes when appropriate. This role ends when the legal proceedings conclude.",
