    "traditional": "有罪",
    "definition": "Responsible for committing a specified offense or wrongdoing. In a legal context, \"guilty\" is the finding or plea that one has committed the crime charged.",
    "legal_usage": "A defendant can be found guilty by a judge/jury verdict or plead guilty as part of a plea bargain. \"Guilty\" is also used colloquially to describe someone who has committed a crime, but in court it's a formal status following conviction. In criminal proceedings, \"not guilty\" is the plea asserting innocence. If a defendant pleads guilty, they waive trial rights and proceed to sentencing. In a courtroom, when the verdict is read, it's stated as \"guilty\" or \"not guilty\" on each count. A guilty verdict must be unanimous in criminal jury trials (in California state courts, except certain misdemeanors by stipulation).",
