    "id": 83,
    "term": "Hung Jury",
    "ipa": "hʌŋ ˈdʒʊri",
    "mk": 7,
    "idi": 4,
    "simplified": "陪审团未能达成一致",
    "traditional": "陪審團未能達成一 致",
    "definition": "A jury that cannot reach a unanimous verdict (in criminal cases) or the required majority verdict (in some civil cases), even after extended deliberation, resulting in no decision.",
    "legal_usage": "A hung jury in a criminal trial means the jurors are deadlocked and cannot all agree on guilty or not guilty. In California criminal cases, the verdict must be unanimous for conviction or acquittal; if, say, 10 jurors vote guilty and 2 vote not guilty and they cannot reach unanimity, the judge may declare a mistrial due to a hung jury. The prosecution must then decide whether to retry the case with a new jury or dismiss the charges. Hung juries are not uncommon in complex or highly contested cases.",
