    "traditional": "起訴書（經大 陪審團）",
    "definition": "A formal written charge issued by a grand jury accusing a person of one or more crimes. It initiates a criminal case in jurisdictions that use grand juries.",
    "legal_usage": "In the federal system and many states, serious charges are brought via indictment after a grand jury finds probable cause. The indictment lists the criminal counts (e.g., \"Count 1: Indictment for burglary...\") California allows prosecution by indictment or by information after a preliminary hearing. If indicted, the defendant will be arraigned on the indictment. Indictments are typically phrased in formal language and can replace a complaint; they often use \"John Doe is hereby indicted for the crime of...\". A sealed indictment remains non-public until the defendant is in custody. An indictment is required for federal felonies under the Fifth Amendment (unless waived).",
