    "simplified": "禁令",
    "traditional": "禁令",
    "definition": "A court order requiring a person or entity to do or cease doing a specific action. Injunctions can be temporary (short-term, emergency) or permanent.",
    "legal_usage": "Injunctions are common in civil cases, especially where monetary damages are insufficient to remedy harm. Types include temporary restraining orders (TRO), preliminary injunctions (issued during a case to maintain status quo), and permanent injunctions (after a final judgment). For example, a court might issue an injunction to stop a company from dumping toxic waste, or to stop someone from contacting or harassing another (see restraining order). In California, to get a preliminary injunction, a plaintiff must show likely success on the merits and potential irreparable harm without it. Violating an injunction can result in contempt of court.",
