    "traditional": "> 在證實有罪前為無罪（無罪推定）",
    "definition": "A fundamental principle of criminal justice stating that the government must prove the accused's guilt; the defendant has no burden to prove innocence and is legally presumed innocent throughout the trial until a verdict is rendered.",
    "legal_usage": "This presumption of innocence is closely tied to the burden of proof on the prosecution to establish guilt beyond a reasonable doubt. Judges instruct juries on this principle at the start of criminal trials. In practice, it means a defendant should be treated as innocent ‒ e.g., allowed bail if appropriate, given due respect (not presented in shackles to jury, etc., unless necessary). The phrase \"innocent until proven guilty\" is a cornerstone of due process and fair trials, embedded in both U.S. law and international human rights law.",
