    "ipa": "ˈlaɪbəl",
    "mk": 4,
    "idi": 4,
    "simplified": "书面诽谤",
    "traditional": "書面誹謗",
    "definition": "A form of defamation expressed in print, writing, pictures, or any communication embodied in physical form that is injurious to a person's reputation. (The spoken form of defamation is slander.)",
    "legal_usage": "Libel is a tort. To prove libel, generally a plaintiff must show a false statement purporting to be fact, publication to a third party, fault amounting to at least negligence, and damages to reputation. Some statements are libel per se (obviously harmful, such as accusing someone of a crime). Public figures (like celebrities or officials) must also prove actual malice (knowledge of falsity or reckless disregard for truth) under U.S. Supreme Court precedent. Libel can also be a crime in rare cases, but it's primarily handled as a civil matter. Retractions can sometimes mitigate damages.",
