    "simplified": "诉讼当事人",
    "traditional": "訴訟當事人",
    "definition": "Any party involved in a lawsuit, such as a plaintiff or defendant in a civil case (or prosecution and defendant in a criminal case, though \"litigant\" is more commonly used in civil contexts).",
    "legal_usage": "Litigants have certain rights and responsibilities: to follow court procedures, to present evidence, etc. In civil cases, both the person suing and the person being sued are litigants. Self-represented litigants (those without attorneys, also called pro per or pro se) must still abide by legal rules. Courts sometimes offer resources for pro se litigants given they might not know procedure. The term emphasizes participation in litigation: e.g., \"the court requires all litigants to attend a settlement conference.\"",
