    "idi": 4,
    "simplified": "调解",
    "traditional": "調解",
    "definition": "An alternative dispute resolution process where a neutral third party (mediator) facilitates a negotiation between disputing parties to help them reach a voluntary, mutually acceptable settlement.",
    "legal_usage": "Mediation is commonly used in civil cases (e.g., divorces, contract disputes, personal injury cases) to avoid the time and expense of trial. The mediator does not have power to impose a decision; instead, they assist communication and propose compromises. In many California courts, mediation is encouraged or even required in certain contexts (like child custody disputes or small claims). Statements in mediation are typically confidential and cannot be used in court if the case doesn't settle. If an agreement is reached, it's put into writing and can be made enforceable as a contract or court order. Mediation is usually quicker and less adversarial than litigation.",
