    "idi": 5,
    "simplified": "轻罪",
    "traditional": "輕罪",
    "definition": "A criminal offense that is less serious than a felony and more serious than an infraction. Misdemeanors are typically punishable by a fine and/or county jail time (usually up to one year), rather than state prison.",
    "legal_usage": "Examples of misdemeanors in California include simple assault, DUI without injury, petty theft, and first-time domestic violence with no great injury. Misdemeanor defendants have the right to a jury trial (usually 12 jurors) and the right to counsel. Sentences are served in county jail. Some offenses can be charged either as misdemeanors or felonies (wobblers). A conviction for a misdemeanor may still carry consequences like probation, community service, and a criminal record, but generally less severe than felonies. California also has a procedure for \"wobbler\" felonies to be reduced to misdemeanors at sentencing or after probation.",
