    "legal_usage": "Courts issue nunc pro tunc orders to correct clerical mistakes or reflect what was intended in an earlier proceeding. For example, if a judge's ruling from last month was not formally entered, the judge can sign a nunc pro tunc order today effective as of the date of the original ruling. This is often used to ensure the record accurately matches the court's actual decision at the time, without conferring unfair advantage.",
