    "legal_usage": "In a jury trial, the prosecution (or plaintiff) delivers the first opening statement, followed by the defense. The opening statement is often called an \"open\" or \"opening argument,\" though it should not argue the law ‒ its purpose is to provide a roadmap of the case. For example, a prosecutor in a murder trial might begin: \"The evidence will show that the defendant had a motive and was seen at the scene...\" The defense's opening then offers their narrative or raises doubts. This sets the stage; while not evidence itself, a powerful opening statement can greatly influence how the jury perceives the upcoming proof.",
