    "legal_usage": "Judges issue an OSC when immediate court supervision is needed. For example, if a parent isn't obeying a custody arrangement, the other parent may get an OSC compelling the non-compliant party to appear and show cause why they should not be held in contempt. In civil cases, an OSC might demand a defendant explain why a preliminary injunction should not be issued. It places the burden on that party to justify their position. Failure to respond to an OSC can result in the requested order being granted by default.",
