    "legal_usage": "Under conspiracy law, the prosecution often must prove at least one overt act committed by one of the conspirators in furtherance of the agreement. For example, a conspiratorial agreement to rob a bank isn't punishable by itself until someone commits an overt act ‒ like buying masks or surveying the bank ‒ to advance the scheme. Similarly, for an attempt charge, an overt act (e.g., pulling out a weapon and moving toward the victim) is required beyond mere preparation. The overt act demonstrates that the crime was not just in planning, but actively underway.",
