    "legal_usage": "Judges often grant O.R. release to defendants deemed low-risk (e.g., first-time offenders or minor charges). The defendant does not pay bail but may face a separate charge or revocation of O.R. if they fail to appear. California law, for example, encourages O.R. release for many misdemeanors. An attorney might argue at a bail hearing, \"My client has strong community ties and no record ‒ we request release on his own recognizance.\" If granted, the defendant is free until trial as long as they honor their promise to return.",
