    "traditional": "赦免",
    "definition": "An act of official forgiveness by the chief executive (governor or President) that releases an individual from punishment and restores their civil rights as if the crime never occurred. A pardon nullifies the legal consequences of a conviction.",
    "legal_usage": "In the U.S., the President can pardon federal offenses, and state governors can pardon state crimes. A full pardon erases guilt and any remaining sentence, often after a conviction. For example, a governor might grant a pardon to someone who has shown rehabilitation long after serving their sentence, thereby reinstating the person's right to vote or own firearms. Accepting a pardon can be seen as an admission of guilt in some jurisdictions. A pardon is different from commutation, which merely reduces a sentence. Courts generally cannot review pardons, as it's an executive prerogative.",
