    "definition": "A conditional release from prison, allowing an inmate to serve the remainder of their sentence under supervision in the community, provided they comply with certain conditions. If conditions are violated, the person can be returned to custody.",
    "legal_usage": "After serving a portion of a prison term (e.g., one-half or two-thirds of the sentence, depending on jurisdiction), an inmate may become eligible for parole. A parole board typically evaluates the prisoner's behavior and rehabilitation to decide on release. Once on parole, the parolee must meet regularly with a parole officer and follow conditions such as maintaining employment, avoiding criminal associates, and not leaving a certain area without permission. If a parolee commits a new crime or breaks rules, a parole revocation hearing can result in them going back to prison. Parole shortens incarceration while still monitoring the offender.",
